{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522070"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13798"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13798"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.09,0.1,0.08,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48946"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48946"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman is referred to the Plastic Surgery clinic with concerns about a pigmented lesion on her ring finger that has been slowly enlarging over the past year. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is visible (image) There is no palpable lymphadenopathy in the axilla or epitrochlear region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and review in 3 months","Cryotherapy","Shave biopsy","Punch biopsy","Excisional biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a suspicious pigmented lesion on her finger that has characteristics concerning for melanoma, including asymmetry, irregular borders, and color variation. The most appropriate next step is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows for complete histological assessment of the lesion, including measurement of Breslow thickness, which is crucial for staging and further management planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and review\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a suspicious pigmented lesion, especially on an acral site like a finger. Melanomas on the hands and feet tend to have a worse prognosis than those on other body sites, partly due to delayed diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated for suspicious pigmented lesions as it destroys the tissue without allowing for histological examination. This could lead to misdiagnosis or delayed diagnosis of a potential melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShave biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for suspected melanomas as it may not provide an accurate assessment of the lesion\u0027s depth, which is crucial for staging and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E, while better than a shave biopsy, is still not ideal for suspected melanomas. It may not capture the full thickness of the lesion and could miss the area with the greatest depth of invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melanomas on the hands and feet have a worse prognosis than those on other body sites.","Suspicious pigmented lesions on acral sites should be biopsied promptly.","Wide local excision with appropriate margins is the standard treatment for cutaneous melanoma."],"references":["Mar V, Soyer H, Button-Sloan A, et al. Diagnosis and management of cutaneous melanoma. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020;49(11):733-739. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/diagnosis-and-management-of-cutaneous-melanoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13798"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20740"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20740"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0Wa8REbmfcPSVu4OdZf9xlbuFpqd0T.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0Wa8REbmfcPSVu4OdZf9xlbuFpqd0T.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T15:34:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T15:34:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48946"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re